published by the Free Software Foundation. A copy of this license is
included in the repository: see "licenses/gpl-3.0-standalone.html".

All files in this repository that are not source code (including images,
videos, sounds and documents) are licensed under the Creative Commons
Attribution-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported License. A copy of this license is
included in the repository: see "licenses/CC-BY-SA-3.0.html".

By sending a contribution to the mailing list, you therefore agree that
it will be licensed either under the version 3 of the GNU General Public
License or under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 3.0 Unported
License -- depending on whether it qualifies as source code or not.
Text files that can be compiled to executable machine code do qualify.

The copyright is shared amongst contributors, who are to be identified
in all git commits. For example, if contributor A provides a new file
"foo", he owns the copyright on that original file. Then if contributor B
provides a patch that changes "foo", he owns the copyright on those
changes.

You are welcome to fork the Triage project. However, when doing so please
use a non ambiguous name for the new project. For example, "Triage 2.0"
would be confusing for the users, whereas "Triphase" would not be ambiguous.
